	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I vote ASM6 because it's at least equally easy to use as NESASM and without the various hiccups of it. With Tokumaru's templates <!-- l --><a class="postlink-local" href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6160">viewtopic.php?t=6160</a><!-- l --> it's very fast to start off with and have a working ROM. And with Ben Samples' iNES macros <!-- l --><a class="postlink-local" href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6990">viewtopic.php?t=6990</a><!-- l --> the iNES header can be written in a more readable manner if that's a problem. I also like that ASM6 is, <s>unlike NESASM</s>, a generic 6502 assembler and doesn't necessarily lock you to NES/Famicom development. <strong>Edit:</strong> NESASM is apparently not locked to NES/Famicom either.<br /><br />The fact that it doesn't have as many functions as ca65 is not a problem for a beginner like me. I'd rather type 6502 code than mess with lots of assembler specific things. And wouldn't the code be more complicated to read if it has too much assembler specific words and stuff? I wouldn't mind trying out ca65 when I get more experienced though.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


