	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />One of the complains I often see about the cc65 suite assembler is that it requires alot of configuration for something simple. Well, configuration is power, but if you want something very simple and dumb, you can do it simply and forget about those linker scripts if you want to. That is, you can turn (use) cl65 as a <em>dumb</em> assembler.<br /><br />Take that for example, I wanted to hack a NSF to study its inner workings, so I used da65 to do so, and with the time I made an good infofile to better instruct the disassembler and separate code and data. When the time to hack the NSF came, I was too lazy to even consider making a linker script for that, it was a rather simple NSF with no bankswitching that loaded into $C000. I tried:<div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">cl65 --target none --start-addr $BF80 disasm.s -o test.nsf<br /></div> (the start address is $C000 - $80 (size of NSF header)), but apparently cl65 doesn't like hexadecimal constants in the command line, but I was <em>really</em> lazy as fuq and so I used since then the following in a tiny script&#058;<div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">cl65 --target none --start-addr $(printf %d 0xBF80) disasm.s -o test.nsf<br /></div><br />I didn't even see the need to use ASM6 or something else for that, cl65 can be as dumb as you want to.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


