	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>zzo38</b> [ Sun Feb 09, 2014 11:34 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Assembler of your choice</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />It seems that <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">ORG</tt> means different things in different assemblers. In ASM6, it pads the output. In MagicKit, only the low thirteen bits are used to set the offset into the output file, but all sixteen bits are used for labels and so on. (In Unofficial MagicKit, it is possible to use a postprocessor to relocate them, but this is not possible in the standard MagicKit.)<br /><br />I read about macros in P65; I do not particularly like that way either (although it does suggest you can use a C preprocessor if you want textual macros). (In Unofficial MagicKit, you can use the <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">ASSIGN</tt> and/or <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">MACSET</tt> command to imitate &quot;binding&quot; of macro parameters.) Macros work in another different way in ACME; it accepts call-by-value and call-by-reference, although not quite like C macros or like MagicKit macros.<br /><br />It is, in fact, possible to tell NESASM/MagicKit not to output a header, and it does in fact allow generic 6502 development; it isn't actually limited to NES/Famicom (although it is one of the two systems it has built-in support for; the other is PC-Engine, although I don't know anything about PC-Engine programming).<br /><br />About passing hexadecimal numbers on the command-line for cl65, I did expect that using C syntax might work since if it is using strtol() then it would accept it (if you don't tell it what base the numbers are in, it will figure out by itself using the prefix).<br /><br />IFDEFs, locally defined labels, and anonymous labels are all supported in MagicKit too (the last one only in Unofficial MagicKit), although none of these are features I find useful for my own uses. I prefer to put everything in one ASM file, with exception of data produced by external programs, if there is any (sometimes there isn't any).<br /><br />MagicKit (including the features I have added) is what fits my style of programming, so that is what I use. (Most people probably have no use for the postprocessor VM, and would rarely use the advanced macros it supports, but I find these features to be very useful.) Another feature I like is explicit zero-page addressing.<br /><br />For anyone who does like some features of NESASM but think it lacks some features or has some bugs, you may want to consider to look at my version of NESASM, which adds some things (described elsewhere on the forum) which you may or may not find useful.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


